snippet.textDisplay: I'm a Holloway fan, but he fought a terrible fight (at least tactically). If a guy hits you 10 times on the legs, the judges may ignore it and it won't effect your ability to fight, but if you let him kick your legs constantly without even bothering to check them, no judge can deny this anymore, and it will effect your movement, as well as give your opponent confidence. Those leg kicks were what separated the two fighters, and one can argue Holloway did not win a single round because of that. The boxing was about even, but even there Volkanovski seemed to land the harder punches. That said, I expected Max to have a hard night, facing a guy with a much bigger frame. It was comparable to the second Poirier fight, where he couldn't oppose his will either due to the strength of the opponent. If a rematch happens, I think the result will be the same, maybe a little closer if he manages to solve the leg kick problem. And if they keep appointing judges who shouldn't even be allowed to color the scoring sheet with a pencil, let alone write a number on it, Max may even get the win.
snippet.textOriginal: I'm a Holloway fan, but he fought a terrible fight (at least tactically). If a guy hits you 10 times on the legs, the judges may ignore it and it won't effect your ability to fight, but if you let him kick your legs constantly without even bothering to check them, no judge can deny this anymore, and it will effect your movement, as well as give your opponent confidence. Those leg kicks were what separated the two fighters, and one can argue Holloway did not win a single round because of that. The boxing was about even, but even there Volkanovski seemed to land the harder punches. That said, I expected Max to have a hard night, facing a guy with a much bigger frame. It was comparable to the second Poirier fight, where he couldn't oppose his will either due to the strength of the opponent. If a rematch happens, I think the result will be the same, maybe a little closer if he manages to solve the leg kick problem. And if they keep appointing judges who shouldn't even be allowed to color the scoring sheet with a pencil, let alone write a number on it, Max may even get the win.

snippet.textDisplay: Im a huge max fan. But after reading a little bit about volkanovski... I'm a fan. We re both born 1988. He started in MMA 2012. That would have made us 24 yrs old, which in most cases (espcially in pro sports) is pretty late. I boxed and did tkd since I was 9 yrs old.  I picked up muay thai at 16 and got serious after I didnt qualify for pan am. I got a neck injury at in 2008. Most of my colleagues who I grew up competing with by that time went pro at either boxing/kB muaynthai and mma. Some by 2007. By 2010 I was no longer active and moved on with my good life. I Got married in 2012 graduated in 2013...started my cateer. life was amazing. and sounds pretty sweet and cool knowing someone out there that year the same age decided to try MMA and now is the champ. Anything is possible.
